      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "rationale": "Grid convergence index (GCI) computed across three systematically refined meshes following Celik et al. (2008) procedure. GCI < 2.3% for velocity magnitude and < 4.1% for wall shear stress. Apparent order of convergence p=1.94 confirms asymptotic range. Richardson extrapolation applied to NIH prediction.",
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/discretization-ac",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Discretization error acceptance criteria",
        "description": "GCI < 5% for QoI-relevant flow quantities across three mesh levels with demonstrated asymptotic convergence. Gradation 2 required at MRL 2; Gradation 3 achieved."
      }
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "rationale": "Experimental test conditions from the FDA benchmark study are well-documented including fluid temperature (37°C), hematocrit (0%), and operating speed/flow combinations. Boundary conditions in the CFD model are matched to the reported experimental conditions within measurement uncertainty.",
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/test-conditions-ac",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Test conditions acceptance criteria",
        "description": "All experimental boundary conditions documented and matched in CFD model within stated measurement uncertainties. Fluid properties, temperature, and operating points must be traceable to experimental records."
      }
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "rationale": "Quantitative comparison metrics computed including mean absolute error, root-mean-square error, and relative error for pressure-flow curves and NIH. Agreement within 15% for NIH and within 4% for pressure-flow across all 5 operating points. Experimental uncertainty bands included in comparison.",
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/output-comparison-ac",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Output comparison acceptance criteria",
        "description": "Quantitative error metrics must be reported with experimental uncertainty. NIH agreement within 20% and pressure-flow agreement within 10% across all operating points. Gradation 2 required and achieved."
      }
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "rationale": "The primary QoI (normalized index of hemolysis, NIH) is directly linked to the clinical endpoint of pump-induced blood trauma. The Giersiepen power-law hemolysis model maps shear stress and exposure time to NIH, which is the regulatory-accepted metric for CPB device hemolysis assessment. QoI relevance to COU decision criterion (RH < 1) is fully established.",
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/qoi-relevance-ac",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "QoI relevance acceptance criteria",
        "description": "QoI must be directly traceable to the clinical decision criterion and regulatory hemolysis metric. NIH and relative hemolysis index RH must be defined with explicit linkage to the COU acceptance threshold RH < 1."
      }
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "rationale": "Validation activities use the FDA generic centrifugal blood pump geometry under CPB-representative operating conditions (flow rates 2–8 L/min, speeds 2000–3500 RPM). The validation domain overlaps with the COU operating envelope. Extrapolation beyond the validated range is not required for the intended COU decision.",
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/validation-relevance-ac",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Validation relevance acceptance criteria",
        "description": "Validation geometry and operating conditions must overlap with the COU envelope. No extrapolation beyond the validated domain is permitted without additional uncertainty quantification. Gradation 2 required and achieved."
      }
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "not-applicable",
      "rationale": "Numerical solver error as a distinct factor from discretization error addresses iterative convergence and round-off contributions in the context of time-dependent or loosely coupled solvers. For this steady-state RANS simulation using a pressure-based coupled solver, iterative residuals converge to machine precision (< 1e-6 for all equations) and round-off error is negligible relative to discretization error already quantified under the Discretization Error factor. ASME V&V 40 Table 3 notes that at MRL 2, this factor may be scoped out when iterative convergence is rigorously demonstrated and the solver is not stochastic or loosely coupled. These conditions are fully satisfied here."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "not-applicable",
      "rationale": "Use error addresses the risk of incorrect model setup or parameter entry by an inexperienced analyst in a production deployment context. For this credibility assessment, the simulation was executed by a single qualified CFD team with documented simulation protocols, peer-reviewed setup checklists, and independent review of boundary condition inputs. There is no end-user deployment scenario in which untrained operators would run the model. The COU is a one-time design-phase regulatory submission, not a recurring clinical workflow tool. Therefore, the use error factor does not apply to this COU at MRL 2."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "not-applicable",
      "rationale": "Model form uncertainty as a separately assessed credibility factor requires independent experimental data at the COU conditions against which the chosen turbulence closure and hemolysis sub-model can be formally evaluated for structural bias. At MRL 2, ASME V&V 40 Table 3 permits this factor to be addressed implicitly through the Output Comparison and Validation Relevance factors rather than through a standalone model-form uncertainty quantification study. The validation results (NIH within 15%, pressure-flow within 4%) demonstrate that model form error is bounded within acceptable limits for the regulatory decision. A separate model-form UQ study is not required and would not change the decision outcome given the demonstrated agreement."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "not-applicable",
      "rationale": "Model inputs uncertainty quantification as a standalone factor addresses parametric sensitivity to uncertain material properties, boundary condition values, and geometric tolerances. At MRL 2, ASME V&V 40 Table 3 allows this factor to be addressed at a reduced level when the primary QoI sensitivity has been established through the validation comparison and when boundary conditions are well-characterized experimentally. The experimental dataset provides blood analog viscosity, density, and pump geometry with documented measurement uncertainties. Sensitivity of NIH to ±10% variation in the hemolysis power-law exponent is addressed under the hasUncertaintyQuantification field of the hemolysis validation result. A full parametric uncertainty propagation study is not required at MRL 2 for a Class II device with medium model influence."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "not-applicable",
      "rationale": "Test samples as a credibility factor addresses the representativeness and variability of physical test specimens used in validation experiments, including manufacturing variability, material lot effects, and sample-to-sample scatter. The FDA benchmark experimental data used for validation was collected on a precision-machined acrylic pump model with documented dimensional tolerances and using a standardized blood analog (glycerin-water mixture). No biological variability or manufacturing lot effects are relevant to the validation dataset. The factor is not applicable because the validation relies on a single reference geometry with negligible specimen variability, consistent with the FDA benchmark study design intent."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "not-applicable",
      "rationale": "Equivalency of input parameters addresses the degree to which the simulation input conditions match the physical test conditions when there is a known or suspected mismatch requiring formal equivalency justification. In this assessment, the CFD model boundary conditions are set directly from the reported experimental measurements (flow rate, rotational speed, fluid properties) with no deliberate substitution or scaling. There is no surrogate input or analog condition requiring equivalency justification. The factor does not apply because the simulation inputs are directly traceable to the experimental conditions without any input transformation or substitution."
    }
  ],
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/decision/morrison-cou1-decision",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/synth/actor/morrison-credibility-lead",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "All seven assessed credibility factors meet or exceed their required gradation levels at MRL 2 for a Class II CPB device. Software quality assurance (Gradation 2 achieved vs. 1 required), numerical code verification (Gradation 2 vs. 1 required), discretization error (Gradation 3 vs. 2 required), test conditions (Gradation 2 vs. 2 required), output comparison (Gradation 2 vs. 2 required), QoI relevance (Gradation 3 vs. 2 required), and validation relevance (Gradation 2 vs. 2 required) are all satisfactory. Six factors are documented as not-applicable with explicit rationale grounded in MRL 2 scope, the steady-state simulation context, the well-characterized experimental dataset, and the one-time regulatory submission use case. Three independent validation results with full uncertainty quantification and provenance chains confirm model predictive accuracy within acceptable bounds. The relative hemolysis index criterion (RH < 1) is achievable within the demonstrated model uncertainty. The credibility evidence is sufficient to support the regulatory submission decision for this Class II CPB device at Medium assurance level.",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z"
  },
